<p>My supervisor, <a href="https://www.ece.ubc.ca/faculty/alireza-nojeh">Dr. Alireza Nojeh</a>, is the organizer for this year‚Äôs
<a href="http://www.vacuumnanoelectronics.org/">International Vacuum Nanoelectronics Conference</a>, and so of
course, I and the <a href="http://nanostructure.ece.ubc.ca/people/">other 7 members</a> of the Nojeh lab have, ahem, ‚Äúvolunteered‚Äù to staff
the conference.</p>

<p>Oh, did that sound like I was unhappy? Not at all! It‚Äôs actually been very fascinating (despite the several hundred collective
man-hours of work) to see the inside work going on in preparing for an event for some of the field‚Äôs best academics, industry
researchers, and up-and-comers to come and brag about their past months‚Äô or even years‚Äô work. Plus, let‚Äôs be honest: I‚Äôm an
undergrad who has had one year of math and physics and has just started working in a electrical engineering graduate research
lab ‚Äì I was feeling completely out of my element, and it has been a nice break to turn my attention to planning and organizing,
which is something I do rather well.</p>

<p>So, what sort of things go into organizing a conference?</p>

<p>Uh, well, mostly printing things and then arranging them into neat piles. Lots and lots of printing‚Ä¶</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/2016/ivnc-conference-papers.jpg" alt="Photo of stacks of printed papers" />
<span class="caption">Small sampling of printed things.</span></p>

<p>‚Ä¶ and spreadsheets‚Ä¶</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/2016/ivnc-spreadsheet1.jpg" alt="Screenshot of spreadsheets" /></p>

